It's not that complicated, you just need to know what they want, and as you said, an anthro wouldn't think the same way a human would, so believe it or not, you have wriggle room.
What a female might want from a relationship socially:
>Safety, security, the ability to relax either via dependability or someone who knows how to keep her nerves tamed
What a female might want from a relationship intimately:
>To feel wanted and valuable, vulnerable but safe, to be able to express without backlash
For example, men might make a move to express attraction, but a female is the type to make a move in order to confirm if their feelings are mutual. The line of thought runs parallel but in different directions. A man focuses on how something looks, a female focuses on the way something looks.
Now, you go from there and think about how animal relationships work, based on species.
>Solitary big cats may want someone to elope with, to feel free and to unwind
>Wolves might want someone who can provide, but keep others in line
>Hyenas probably just want someone who will support them, but with minimal fuss and help keep them calm
I'd like to provide some prey animal examples, but the less intelligent the harder this gets. I don't recommend following this 1:1 either, because it'll get boring fast and interesting characters are also contrived.
